sby (Lincolnshire), or either of two places called Ormesby in Norfolk and the North Yorkshire. The placenames all derive from the Old Norse personal name <i>Ormr</i> + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’. This surname is also common in Ireland (Connacht), where it has been established since the late 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":18,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":91,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Ormesby was born in 1364, in Lincolnshire, England as the son of Richard Ormesby. He had at least 1 daughter with Robert Ormbsy Mrs."},"et":{"1364–":"1364–Surnud","1364–Male":"1364–Surnud","1368–Female":"1368–Surnud","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1396–Male":"1396–Surnud","1332–Male":"1332–Surnud","1368":"1368","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1332":"1332","1364":"1364","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","Of, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Portown, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1364–":"1364–Kuollut","1364–Male":"1364–Kuollut","1368–Female":"1368–Kuollut","1400–Female":"1400–Kuollut","1396–Male":"1396–Kuollut","1332–Male":"1332–Kuollut","1368":"1368","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1332":"1332","1364":"1364","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","Of, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Portown, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fr":{"1364–":"1364–Décédé","1364–Male":"1364–Décédé","1368–Female":"1368–Décédée","1400–Female":"1400–Décédée","1396–Male":"1396–Décédé","1332–Male":"1332–Décédé","1368":"1368","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1332":"1332","1364":"1364","1396":"1396","1382":"1382","Of, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Portown, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert Ormesby est né en 1364, à Lincolnshire, Angleterre, fils de Richard Ormesby. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Robert Ormbsy Mrs."},"de":{"1364–":"1364–Verstorben","1364–Male":"1364–Verstorben","1368–Female":"1368–Verstorben","1400–Female":"1400–Verstorben","1396–Male":"1396–Verstorben","1332–Male":"1332–Verst